task.summary: Default task

Fixing a serious bug with putStatic and putField instructions.
The bug was to do with how we fill up FIELD_OUTPUT holes (which are created for both putStatic and putField instructions, with the putStatic ones having FieldInfo.localStackSlot set to -1 and putField ones having Field.localStackSlot set to the local variable's stack slot from where the object reference will be read).
For FIELD_OUTPUT holes, we would simply set them to be output variables of a region and write them into the corresponding field in a veritesting region. But, if a putStatic or putField for the same field was encountered on both sides of a branch, then this would cause two writes into the same field, which is wrong.
We now create a intermediate variable hole and set it inside FIELD_OUTPUT hole's FieldInfo.writeVal. This is used to lookup the variable to be written into the field. This intermediate variable takes on a value depending on which side of the branch was taken.
1. Adding support for getStatic instructions 2. Changing the key for veritesting regions to a hash code computed using Fowler-Noll-Vo (FNV) algorithm
Minor code re-arrangements to bring down veritesting region's use time.
Committing FNV files
Recording time taken for various parts of solving and reporting them in the VeritestingListener using PublisherExtension
Converting nanoseconds to milliseconds once we are done recording time This finally makes totalSolverTime = z3Time + parsingTime + solverAllocTime + cleanupTime
Using the method signature as part of the key to the hashmap of veritesting regions
1. Adding support for nested veritesting regions 2. Checking equivalence between SPF and SPF-veritesting in WBS 3. Adding tcas2 which is tcas that runs two steps

Minor changes 1. Use VeritestingListener to record statistics even when veritesting is turned off 2. Use a single assert call in WBS 3. Add static analysis time to report published in VeritestingListener
Counting regions run into and used more precisely.
Adding ran-into, used counts into the region objects and printing it out in the VeritestingListener

1. Each region now contains its starting and ending basic block numbers, a HashSet containing starting basic block number of each region inside it 2. Reporting the number of regions along with number of times each region was run into and used based on the number of branches summarized in that region

Adding method summarization for methods with more than one execution path in them.
This is done by first finding veritesting regions within all methods that need to be summarized. Then we stitch the method summary by using veritesting regions found within each method.
Adding some more statistics to measure method summary usage.
1. Capturing as many classes as possible for region finding and summarization 2. Fixing method signatures to use canonical name instead of simple name
1. Fixing issue where SPF fails to load a class when resolving field input holes 2. Committing an initial version of veritestingMode which can toggle veritesting off by setting veritestingMode to 0

1. Finishing veritestingMode. This is a configuration option that has to be specified in the jpf file. It is set up as follows: - veritestingMode = 1 -> run vanilla SPF using VeritestingListener. In this case VeritestingListener will be useful to report solver-related statistics. - veritestingMode = 2 -> run veritesting with simple regions (regions that do not include other regions) only. - veritestingMode = 3 -> run veritesting with complex regions (regions that include other regions). - veritestingMode = 4 -> run veritesting with complex regions and method summaries 2. Adding a ending bytecode offset to method summaries.

1. Fixing the read-after-write bug. If a local variable or field is read after it has already been written to inside a region, then the read should return the last value that was written. 2. Adding support for use of static fields in method summaries

Allowing a method summary included in a outer region to use static and non-static fields. Veritesting of the outer region is performed only if any local objects used for field inputs inside the method summary can be filled by the outer region.
FIELD_OUTPUT holes can also access static or non-static objects for completing the field access.

Adding configuration options and tracking metrics for readAfterWrite, writeAfterRead, and writeAfterWrite operations on fields. Enabling writeAfterRead on fields for now since it is required to do veritesting in the VeritestingPerf.countBitsSet method. Corresponding metrics for how many regions were missed are reported in VeritestingListener.
Checking if a method summary has a read-write interference with the outer region, if it does, give up on veritesting the outer region.
1. Adding support for logical_not operator especially for use in GreenConstraint 2. Allowing write-after-write and write-after-read operations for now
1. Allowing multiple outputs to be phi'd at the end of a veritesting region 2. Refactoring VeritestingListener.fillHoles() in preparation of implementing higher-order regions

Adding support for comparing object references dynamically when computing a read-write interference between a outer region and a method summary.
Previously we would compare field information to find a intersection, but comparing object references at runtime is the right way to do it.
Looking up a field based on the dynamic class type of the object reference instead of using the static class type.

1. Converting the HashMap of holes to a LinkedHashMap because it maintains the order in which holes are created. This is useful because nested field accesses need previously created holes corresponding to an intermediate object reference to be resolved before the current field access can be resolved. 2. Adding support for nested field accesses.

1. Adding support for nested field writes (the previous commit had only tested nested field reads) 2. Refactoring the code so that fillFieldInputHole and fillFieldOutputHole are now merged into a single fillFieldHole parameterized by a read/write operator specified as a boolean

During a field access, the object reference should be loaded from a previously created hole before being loaded from a local variable stack slot. This is because while the previously created hole (in FieldInfo.useHole) would be mapped to the right object reference, the local stack slot will contain the object reference present at the beginning of or before the region.
Refactoring to have only one method to fill non-input holes

1. Supporting higher order regions (tested up to the 3rd order) 2. Fix a bug to allow an empty method summary to be used 3. Separating method summary filling into a separate FillMethodSummary class in VeritestingListener 4. Separating invoke hole filling into a separate FillInvokeHole class in VeritestingListener
The use of a method summary will always involve the use of a invoke hole. FillInvokeHole will call FillMethodSummary to fill the method summary in. If the method summary involves a method call, FillMethodSummary will call FillInvokeHole to summarize the method call.
When filling a invoke hole in a method summary, use the caller hole's global or local stack slot, in that order, so that the invoked method gets the global stack slot if available.

1. Fixing a bug with higher order regions that, if a invoked method itself invokes another method, adds holes from the caller's parameters into the method's holeHashMap 2. Adding a classname, methodname to every hole so that, for local input/output holes, we can figure out if the global stack slot or the local stack slot is to be used. The global stack slot is used only if the current (current-className, current-methodName) != (hole-className, hole-methodName)

1. Fixing a bug with read-after-write support that was causing an unsat query to be constructed. The fix is to disable use of VarUtil.varCache when we create an intermediate variable for field output holes. This causes every write operation to create a new hole. This fix along with the tracking-of-latest-write-before-read implementation fixes the two WALA IR SSA form issues that were causing problems with read-after-write accesses with the same field. 2. Fixing an issue with the class name populated for field input and field output holes. The hole should have the current region's class name, not the field's class name.
Adding support for static field accesses in higher-order regions

Adding support for phi functions on field accesses. Point 4 in Solution is in progress - doing a recursive copy of HoleExpression.FieldInfo.PLAssign is pending.
* field output issues addressed in this commit: * two writes in parallel (one on then-side, one on else-side of a branch) now cause two intermediate variables to be written out to the same field one after the other * if a field is modified on the then side but not modified on the else side, the region’s output should also honor the choice of leaving the field unaltered * read-after-write and write-after-write operations are reported even if the two operations are on different sides of a branch * Solution: 1. Every field output hole should also have the output’s corresponding path predicate. 2. Detecting read-after-write and write-after-write should also check the path predicate for equality. 3. During populateOutputs, all outputs written to the same field with the isLatestWrite bit set should first be accumulated. Next we should read the existing value V of the field. Finally, the field value should be a intermediate variable that is equal to (p1 => v1) || (p2 => v2) || … || V 4. When an outer region gobbles up an inner region, every field output path predicate of the inner region should be conjuncted with the outer region’s current path predicate
1. Fixing an unsat bug with phi-expressions that are created for fields. 2. Restructuring the aliasing detection to use the call site parameters for locals if it is not null

1. Remove the isHole boolean from HoleExpression because we will never have a HoleExpression object that is not a hole 2. Get field updates working on Mike's testSimple1 test case (the one reduced from WBS I think)

Getting field updates to satisfy all testSimple* test cases except the testSimple test case. VeritestingPerf.testSimple() fails because it calls simpleRegion() and uses its return value in assertions later. But testSimple() itself is not summarized because of unhandled AssertionError cases in it. The method summary of simpleRegion() is instantiated and used. But we never push the return value's symbolic formula on the stack after instantiating testSimple(). This causes testSimple()'s first assertion to fail.
To get testSimple() to pass, I need to a instantiated method summary to actually return a symbolic formula.
Make the read-after-write, write-after-write analysis to use dynamic object aliases instead of being static. This is still an initial draft of the implementation and I am currently testing it.
Somewhat working implementation of field updates where read-after-writes and write-after-writes are also supported and correctly calculated using the dynamic object types

Giving fields a static class name and a dynamic class name.
The dynamic class name is useful when figuring out the field access in fillFieldHole.
Word of caution: Never use the fieldStaticClassName for comparison

A periodic commit to add bug fixes on field updates. These now pass all of Mike's test cases. But we are still unable to veritest with nested region (VeritestingPerf.nestedRegion) and higer-order region (VeritestingPerf.countBitsSet) test cases.
Another periodic commit. Everything seems to be working for now, but it needs to be tested some more.

Removing the stack slots (localStackSlot and callSiteStackSlot) from FieldInfo. From now on, we will use a total of 2 stack slots in every HoleExpression object, a local stack slot and a global stack slot.
The global stack slot maintains the stack slot from the outermost region.

1. Doing read-write interference-checking across higher-order regions instead of only checking every region with its adjacent region in the invoke call-chain. 2. Updating the global stack slot only if the context (classname, methodname) of a hole does not match the outermost region's context.

1. Writes to fields in higher-order regions should persist beyond the outermost region 2. FIELD_OUTPUTs may not always have a hole as their writeValue. Use the hole hashmap only if the writeValue is a hole.
Simplifying the construction of symbolic formulas when equating parameters in a method summary
Committing workspace.xml
